sed both the law and economic analysis to challenge racial inequities and deprivations.   This volume—a recovery of Sadie Alexander’s economic thought—provides a comprehensive account of her thought-provoking speeches and writings on the relationship between democracy, race, and justice. Nina Banks’s introductions bring fresh insight into the events and ideologies that underpinned Alexander’s outlook and activism. A brilliant intellectual, Alexander called for bold, redistributive policies that would ensure racial justice for Black Americans while also providing a foundation to safeguard democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American women civil rights workersxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American women civil rights workerszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 0aDemocracy. 0aJustice. 0aMinority economistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRacism. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Speeches.2bisacsh1 aBanks, Nina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300260861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300260861.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles